    abstract = {The notions of ionicity and covalency of chemical bonds, effective atomic charges, and decomposition of the cohesive energy into ionic and covalent terms are fundamental yet elusive. For example, different approaches give different values of atomic charges. Pursuing the goal of formulating a universal approach based on firm physical grounds (first-principles or non-empirical), we develop a formalism based on Wannier functions with atomic orbital symmetry and capable of defining these notions and giving numerically robust results that are in excellent agreement with traditional chemical thinking. Unexpectedly, in diamond-like boron phosphide (BP), we find charges of +0.68 on phosphorus and -0.68 on boron atoms, and this anomaly is explained by the Zintl-Klemm nature of this compound. We present a simple model that includes energies of the highest occupied cationic and lowest unoccupied anionic atomic orbitals, coordination numbers, and strength of interatomic orbital overlap. This model captures the essential physics of bonding and accurately reproduces all our results, including anomalous BP.},
    annotate = {The main point seems to be an energy decomposition into ionic and covalent cohesive energy, but I read it for the computation of partial charges. Like my partial charge estimates, boron phosphide has a negative charge on boron, and also like me, they get a postive boron in boron nitride. There's a long discussion of the boron phosphide result in a section titled ``The peculiar case of BP''. There's also a positive charge on carbon in carbon monoxide, discussed in the third item of an enumerated list at the beginning of the results section. Both BP and CO are said to be explained by the Zintl-Klemm rule. There's also another explanation, in which neutral boron can make three bonds, but boron anion can make four. That seems to make sense in Lewis structures, and seems to correspond to how in organic molecules, we consider tetravalent nitrogen to have a formal positive chage. It seems handwavy. I guess the same reasoning applies to boron nitride, but we have to somehow balance this reasoning against the electronegativity difference? And I don't suppose there's any way to say beforehand how much to weight each consideration. It's like we're balancing nitrogen's covalent formal positivity with its electronegativity. But Figure 1 makes it look like it's more about how the boundaries between atoms are drawn, which seems to undermine all this reasoning.},
    issn = {0021-9606},
    doi = {10.1063/5.0202481},
    url = {https://doi.org/10.1063/5.0202481},
    eprint = {https://pubs.aip.org/aip/jcp/article-pdf/doi/10.1063/5.0202481/19876178/144113_1_5.0202481.pdf},
}
@article{Nakano1997,
