abstract={Charge equilibration models such as the electronegativity equalization method (EEM) and the split charge equilibration (SQE) are extensively used in the literature for the efficient computation of accurate atomic charges in molecules. However, there is no consensus on a generic set of optimal parameters, even when one only considers parameters calibrated against atomic charges in organic molecules. In this work, the origin of the disagreement in the parameters is investigated by comparing and analyzing six sets of parameters based on two sets of molecules and three calibration procedures. The resulting statistical analysis clearly indicates that the conventional least-squares cost function based solely on atomic charges is in general ill-conditioned and not capable of fixing all parameters in a charge-equilibration model. Methodological guidelines are formulated to improve the stability of the parameters. Although in this case a simple interpretation of individual parameters is not possible, charge equilibration models remain of great practical use for the computation of atomic charges.},
annotate={This paper shows that the minima of QEq training loss functions have near-singular subspaces. The lowest eigenvalue corresponds to adjustment of the electronegativity and hardness of fluorine, which is unsurprising: how can you determine hardness if charge doesn't vary? Even in my regression framing, no variation, no confidence in effect. Verstraelen doesn't seem to think underdetermination of the parameters is a real issue, since all these parameters make the same predictions anyway. It's hard to say; we want to extrapolate, but we don't expect to have to make predictions on neutral fluorine, do we? Figure 3 shows that in a chlorine-containing molecule, there's seemingly no change in charge prediction when adjusting the parameters along an eigenvector that involves the parameters of chlorine. In a discussion of the binary system predictions (equation 18), Toon explains why you get this kind of underdetermination: an increase in electronegativity can be compensated by a decrease in hardness. That makes sense because electronegativity increases charge transfer and hardness decreases it. At least for fluorine which is always more electronegative them whatever it is bonded to; once there's elements on either side of it, electronegativity and hardness will have different effects. More relevant to my own work, he discusses that these ambiguities could be resolved by including external potentials, though the paper doesn't seem to do that. It seems that this would disambiguate electronegativity and hardness because hardness scales the response to the external field, though I didn't see him say that directly anywhere. One odd thing about this paper is the loss function in equation 4. It softens the charge constraint so that you don't need to have perfect integer charge. I don't understand the motivation for this, because the reference charges we're trying to predict have this constraint, so it's like we're throwing away information. He claims that if you do this you can determine the electronegativity parameters without having to standardize to an arbitrary reference value. It seems impossible at first, but the trick is using the Mulliken electronegativity in defining the loss of function. This means that he's doing simulations of ions. If you're doing simulations of ions then you can break the total charge constraint that makes the electronegativity underdetermined. If I had good ion simulations I would just include them in the training data and determine the absolute electronegativity that way.},
issn={1549-9618},
doi={10.1021/ct200006e},
url={https://doi.org/10.1021/ct200006e}
}
