    annotate = {Definition of the electronegativity of a system, in equation 12. A disappointing result that the Thomas-Fermi theory cannot give you electronegativities of atoms; in section VI it is argued that they will always be computed to be zero. Atomic electronegativities are discussed in section IX, ``Atoms in molecules''. That leads to formula 75, a relationship between the energy difference and the squared chemical potential difference. Of course in the linear electronegativity model, the proportionality constant is related to the ``total hardness''. Here, it is shown to be some functional of the atomic densities. The atomic electronegativities depend on a quantity ``Q'', which is introduced in a ``Gibbs-Duhem equation'' in section V, in equation 22. It seems that there is a lot to learn here not just about the electronegativity of the system, but about electronegativities of atoms in molecules, which I had previously thought were not introduced until the Mortier-Ghosh-Shankar electronegativity equalization paper.}
